ale":"1370–Deceased","1366–Male":"1366–Deceased","1392–1420":"1392–1420","1394–1443":"1394–1443","1346–Male":"1346–Deceased","Abt 1370":"about 1370","1346":"1346","1443":"1443","1366":"1366","1420":"1420","1394":"1394","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Knight","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: status or occupational name from Middle English <i>knight</i> ‘retainer, attendant’ (Old English <i>cniht</i> ‘boy, youth, lad)’. The specialized feudal sense ‘a high-ranking tenant bound to serve his lord as a mounted soldier’ is not known to have ever given rise to the surname, although it is not out of the question that it may occasionally have been used as a nickname, perhaps for someone who played the part of an armed knight in a local pageant.","Irish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac an Ridire</b> ‘son of the knight’. See also   McKnight  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Knights","meanings":["English (East Anglia): variant of   Knight  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"McKnight","meanings":["Irish: part translation of Gaelic <b>Mac an Ridire</b> ‘son of the horseman (Gaelic <i>ridire</i>)’, formerly Anglicized <i>McRuddery</i>.","Scottish (Dumfriesshire and Galloway) and Irish (Ulster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Neachtain</b>, which is usually Anglicized as   McNaughton  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Knight was born about 1370 as the daughter of Knight. She married Simon Corbet about 1391, in Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"Abt 1370–Deceased":"umbes 1370–Surnud","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1366–Male":"1366–Surnud","1392–1420":"1392–1420","1394–1443":"1394–1443","1346–Male":"1346–Surnud","Abt 1370":"umbes 1370","1346":"1346","1443":"1443","1366":"1366","1420":"1420","1394":"1394","1392":"1392","1370":"1370"},"fi":{"Abt 1370–Deceased":"noin 1370–Kuollut","1370–Female":"1370–Kuollut","1366–Male":"1366–Kuollut","1392–1420":"1392–1420","1394–1443":"1394–1443","1346–Male":"1346–Kuollut","Abt 1370":"noin 1370","1346":"1346","1443":"1443","1366":"1366","1420":"1420","1394":"1394","1392":"1392","1370":"1370"},"fr":{"Abt 1370–Deceased":"environ 1370–Décédée","1370–Female":"1370–Décédée","1366–Male":"1366–Décédé","1392–1420":"1392–1420","1394–1443":"1394–1443","1346–Male":"1346–Décédé","Abt 1370":"environ 1370","1346":"1346","1443":"1443","1366":"1366","1420":"1420","1394":"1394","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","lifeSummary":"Margaret Knight est née environ 1370, fille de Knight. Elle a épousé Simon Corbet environ 1391, à Shropshire, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 2 fils."},